Which he did...

I planned this move because I didn't want to bxc double my pawns in the c column, or worse dxc to have doubled pawns and no castling option after a queen exchange. I know there is no safe retreat for his knight. The early mate threat seemed too good to resist too...
I chose dxc6 as I like the position of my queen already, and it releases my light square bishop.

I don't much like the look of his Queen sitting behind his bishop pointing at my quite empty looking defenses. I thought about playing b5, but bd4 seemed like it was a better, more aggressive move. He has to react to me, instead of building an attack.
